Preheat your oven to 220°C. Remove the @puff pastry sheet{3/4} from your fridge. Heat a 
drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Add the @chicken breast{260%g}(diced), 
season with @pepper{} and cook until brown all over, ~{5-6%minutes}. Turn occasionally. While the 
chicken cooks, thinly slice the @chestnut mushrooms{150%g}, then halve, peel and chop the 
@echalion shallot{1} into small pieces. Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(roughly chopped) 
(stalks and all). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Once the chicken 
has browned (we'll finish cooking it later), transfer to a #bowl{} and set aside.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Pop your frying pan back on medium-high heat (no need to wash). Add a drizzle of @oil{} and the 
@British smoked bacon lardons{60%g}. Stir-fry for ~{1-2%minutes}, then add the mushrooms and 
@wild mushroom paste{15%g}. Stir together and cook until the mushrooms are browned and the onion 
has softened, ~{5-6%minutes}, stirring occasionally. Add the garlic and chicken, stir and cook 
for ~{1%minute}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw meat. Cook lardons thoroughly.

Pour the @water for the sauce{150%ml} into the pan with the chicken and vegetables, then add the 
wild mushroom paste. Stir to combine and bring to the boil. Simmer until reduced by half, 
~{3-4%minutes}. Stir in the @creme fraiche{150%g} and half the parsley, then bring to the boil. 
Remove from the heat, then mix through the @truffle zest{1}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Pour the pie filling into an appropriately sized #ovenproof dish{}. Lay the pastry on top of the 
filling and trim the edges to the size of the dish. Brush the pastry with a little @milk{} if you 
have some. Make a small hole in the middle of the pastry lid with the tip of a sharp #knife{} to 
allow steam to escape. Pop the dish onto a large #baking tray{} (to catch any drips) and bake on 
the middle shelf of your oven until golden brown and bubbly, ~{15-20%minutes}. Meanwhile, trim the 
@tri-coloured Chantenay carrots{225%g} and halve any large ones lengthways (no need to peel).

== Honey Butter Glazed Chantenay Carrots ==

Pour the @water for the carrots{75%ml} into a #saucepan{}. Add the carrots, @honey{15%g}, 
@unsalted butter{20%g} and a @salt{pinch}. Bring to the boil on high heat, then cover the pan 
with a #lid{} or some #foil{}. Reduce the heat to medium and cook the carrots until tender, 
~{10-12%minutes}. Once tender, remove the lid and allow the liquid to boil until it's glossy and 
coats the carrots, ~{2-4%minutes}.

> TIP: If your honey has hardened, pop it in a bowl of hot water for 1 min.

> TIP: If your sauce needs longer to get sticky, transfer the carrots to a bowl and continue 
boiling on a high heat until reduced.

Once the chicken and bacon pie is cooked, serve on plates with the carrots alongside and the 
remaining parsley sprinkled over. Enjoy!